To determine the likely reason for choosing a quality factor range of [30, 70] for JPEG compression instead of a wider range like [10, 90], we need to understand how JPEG compression works and what the quality factor represents. The quality factor (QF) controls the trade-off between image fidelity and file size. A lower QF means more compression and more lossy distortion, while a higher QF means less compression and better fidelity.

The range [30, 70] is commonly used in research and practical applications because it strikes a balance between perceptual quality and computational efficiency. Values below 30 tend to introduce severe artifacts (e.g., blockiness, blurring), which can make images unrecognizable or degrade semantic content. Values above 70, while preserving high fidelity, often result in unnecessarily large files and may not provide perceptible improvements for human viewers.

Thus, the choice of [30, 70] is likely motivated by the goal of ensuring perceptually minimal perturbations while preserving semantic content — aligning with option A.

