The text immediately following the equation explains:  
*“Here, $\mathcal{W}$ is the set of sampled worlds in an update, $N_w$ is the number of agents in world $w$, and $\mathcal{L}_\pi^{(w,i)}$ is the policy loss for agent $i$ in world $w$. We apply the same reweighting to the value loss. This normalization makes each world contribute more evenly regardless of density and reduces the variance amplification induced by highly interactive dense scenes.”*

This indicates that the loss function is weighted inversely by the number of agents ($N_w$) in each world. Worlds with more agents (dense traffic) are given lower weights, while sparse worlds (fewer agents) are given higher weights. This ensures that the gradient updates are balanced across different traffic densities.

Thus, the correct answer is:

**B. It weights each world's loss inversely by its agent count, so dense worlds contribute less to the gradient than sparse worlds.**

